# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: containerd
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:containerd/container-virtualization] In software engineering, **containerization** is operating-system-level virtualization or application-level virtualization over multiple resources so that software applications can run in isolated user spaces called *containers* in any cloud or non-cloud environment, regardless of type or vendor.
[src:containerd/container-virtualization] The term "container" has different meanings in different contexts, and it is important to ensure that the intended definition aligns with the audience's understanding.
[src:containerd/container-virtualization] Each *container* is basically a fully functional and portable cloud or non-cloud computing environment surrounding the application and keeping it independent of other environments running in parallel.
[src:containerd/container-virtualization] Individually, each container simulates a different software application and runs isolated processes by bundling related configuration files, libraries and dependencies.
[src:containerd/container-virtualization] But, collectively, multiple containers share a common operating system kernel (OS).
[src:containerd/container-virtualization] In recent times, containerization technology has been widely adopted by cloud computing platforms like Amazon Web Services, Microsoft Azure, Google Cloud Platform, and IBM Cloud.
[src:containerd/container-virtualization] Containerization has also been pursued by the U.S.
[src:containerd/container-virtualization] Department of Defense as a way of more rapidly developing and fielding software updates, with first application in its F-22 air superiority fighter.
[src:containerd/container-virtualization] Container orchestration or container management is mostly used in the context of application containers.
[src:containerd/container-virtualization] Implementations providing such orchestration include Kubernetes and Docker swarm.
[src:containerd/container-virtualization] This includes functionality to create a cluster, to upgrade the software or repair it, balance the load between existing instances, scale by starting or stopping instances to adapt to the number of users, to log activities and monitor produced logs or the application itself by querying sensors.
[src:containerd/container-virtualization] Open-source implementations of such software include OKD and Rancher.
[src:containerd/container-virtualization] Quite a number of companies provide container cluster management as a managed service, like Alibaba, Amazon, Google, and Microsoft.
[src:containerd/containerd] The **Cloud Native Computing Foundation** (**CNCF**) is a subsidiary of the Linux Foundation founded in 2015 to support cloud-native computing.
[src:containerd/containerd] It was announced alongside Kubernetes 1.0, an open source container cluster manager, which was contributed to the Linux Foundation by Google as a seed technology.
[src:containerd/containerd] Founding members include Google, CoreOS, Mesosphere, Red Hat, Twitter, Huawei, Intel, RX-M, Cisco, IBM, Docker, Univa, and VMware.
[src:containerd/containerd] Today, CNCF is supported by over 450 members.
[src:containerd/containerd] In August 2018 Google announced that it was handing over operational control of Kubernetes to the community.
[src:containerd/open-container-initiative] The **Open Container Initiative** (**OCI**) is a Linux Foundation project, started in June 2015 by Docker, CoreOS, and the maintainers of appc (short for "App Container") to design open standards for operating system-level virtualization (containers).
[src:containerd/open-container-initiative] At launch, OCI was focused on Linux containers and subsequent work has extended it to other operating systems.
[src:containerd/open-container-initiative] There are currently three OCI specifications in development and use: the *Runtime Specification* (runtime-spec), the *Image Specification* (image-spec), and the *Distribution Specification* (distribution-spec).
[src:containerd/open-container-initiative] The OCI Image Format Project was split out from the Runtime Project into its own specification on March 23, 2016.
[src:containerd/open-container-initiative] The image-spec is a software shipping container image format spec (OCI Image Format) that reached version 1.0.0 on July 19, 2017.
[src:containerd/open-container-initiative] The OCI Distribution Spec Project defines the distribution-spec, an API protocol to facilitate and standardize the distribution of content.
[src:containerd/open-container-initiative] The distribution-spec was created on March 8, 2018, from a Proposal for a JSON Registry API V2.1.
[src:containerd/open-container-initiative] The distribution-spec reached version 1.0.0 on April 26, 2021.
[src:containerd/os-level-virtualization] On Unix-like operating systems, this feature can be seen as an advanced implementation of the standard chroot mechanism, which changes the apparent root folder for the current running process and its children.
[src:containerd/os-level-virtualization] In addition to isolation mechanisms, the kernel often provides resource-management features to limit the impact of one container's activities on other containers.
[src:containerd/os-level-virtualization] Linux containers are all based on the virtualization, isolation, and resource management mechanisms provided by the Linux kernel, notably Linux namespaces and cgroups.
[src:containerd/os-level-virtualization] Although the word *container* most commonly refers to OS-level virtualization, it is sometimes used to refer to fuller virtual machines operating in varying degrees of concert with the host OS, such as Microsoft's Hyper-V containers.
[src:containerd/os-level-virtualization] For an overview of virtualization since 1960, see Timeline of virtualization technologies.
[src:containerd/os-level-virtualization] On ordinary operating systems for personal computers, a computer program can see (even though it might not be able to access) all the system's resources.
[src:containerd/os-level-virtualization] The operating system may allow or deny access to such resources based on which program requests them and the user account in the context in which it runs.
[src:containerd/os-level-virtualization] The operating system may also hide those resources, so that when the computer program enumerates them, they do not appear in the enumeration results.
[src:containerd/os-level-virtualization] Nevertheless, from a programming point of view, the computer program has interacted with those resources and the operating system has managed an act of interaction.
[src:containerd/os-level-virtualization] With operating-system-virtualization, or containerization, it is possible to run programs within containers, to which only parts of these resources are allocated.
[src:containerd/os-level-virtualization] A program expecting to see the whole computer, once run inside a container, can only see the allocated resources and believes them to be all that is available.
[src:containerd/os-level-virtualization] Several containers can be created on each operating system, to each of which a subset of the computer's resources is allocated.
[src:containerd/os-level-virtualization] Each container may contain any number of computer programs.
[src:containerd/os-level-virtualization] These programs may run concurrently or separately, and may even interact with one another.
[src:containerd/os-level-virtualization] Containerization has similarities to application virtualization: In the latter, only one computer program is placed in an isolated container and the isolation applies to file system only.
[src:containerd/os-level-virtualization] Operating-system level virtualization is commonly used in virtual hosting environments, where it is useful for securely allocating finite hardware resources among a large number of mutually-distrusting users.
[src:containerd/os-level-virtualization] System administrators may also use it for consolidating server hardware by moving services on separate hosts into containers on the one server.
[src:containerd/os-level-virtualization] Operating-system level virtualization can also be used to run software created for a certain Linux distribution on another distribution, an example is Distrobox.
[src:containerd/os-level-virtualization] Other typical scenarios include separating several programs to separate containers for improved security, hardware independence, and added resource management features.
[src:containerd/os-level-virtualization] The improved security provided by the use of a chroot mechanism, however, is not perfect.
[src:containerd/os-level-virtualization] Operating-system-level virtualization implementations capable of live migration can also be used for dynamic load balancing of containers between nodes in a cluster.
[src:containerd/os-level-virtualization] This form of virtualization also does not require hardware support for efficient performance.
[src:containerd/os-level-virtualization] Operating-system level virtualization is not as flexible as other virtualization approaches since it cannot host a guest operating system different from the host one, or a different guest kernel.
[src:containerd/os-level-virtualization] For example, with Linux, different distributions are fine, but other operating systems such as Windows cannot be hosted.
[src:containerd/os-level-virtualization] Operating systems using variable input systematics are subject to limitations within the virtualized architecture.
[src:containerd/os-level-virtualization] Adaptation methods including cloud-server relay analytics maintain the OS-level virtual environment within these applications.
[src:containerd/os-level-virtualization] Solaris partially overcomes the limitation described above with its branded zones feature, which provides the ability to run an environment within a container that emulates an older Solaris 8 or 9 version in a Solaris 10 host.
[src:containerd/os-level-virtualization] However, in 2010 Linux branded zones were removed from Solaris; in 2014 they were reintroduced in Illumos, which is the open source Solaris fork, supporting 32-bit Linux kernels.
[src:containerd/os-level-virtualization] Some implementations provide file-level copy-on-write (CoW) mechanisms.
[src:containerd/os-level-virtualization] (Most commonly, a standard file system is shared between partitions, and those partitions that change the files automatically create their own copies.) This is easier to back up, more space-efficient and simpler to cache than the block-level copy-on-write schemes common on whole-system virtualizers.
[src:containerd/os-level-virtualization] Whole-system virtualizers, however, can work with non-native file systems and create and roll back snapshots of the entire system state.
[src:containerd/page] Welcome to the containerd documentation!
[src:containerd/page] This document contains some basic project-level information about containerd.
[src:containerd/page] If you’d like to get started running containerd locally on your machine, see the getting started guide.
[src:containerd/page] The containerd project is encapsulated in a variety of GitHub repositories; see https://github.com/containerd .
[src:containerd/releases] This document details the versioning and release plan for containerd.
[src:containerd/releases] Stability is a top goal for this project, and we hope that this document and the processes it entails will help to achieve that.
[src:containerd/releases] It covers the release process, versioning numbering, backporting, API stability and support horizons.
[src:containerd/releases] If you rely on containerd, it would be good to spend time understanding the areas of the API that are and are not supported and how they impact your project in the future.
[src:containerd/releases] This document will be considered a living document.
[src:containerd/releases] Supported timelines, backport targets and API stability guarantees will be updated here as they change.
[src:containerd/releases] If there is something that you require or this document leaves out, please reach out by filing an issue .
[src:containerd/releases] Releases of containerd will be versioned using dotted triples, similar to Semantic Version .
[src:containerd/releases] For the purposes of this document, we will refer to the respective components of this triple as `<major>.<minor>.<patch>`.
[src:containerd/releases] The version number may have additional information, such as alpha, beta and release candidate qualifications.
[src:containerd/releases] Such releases will be considered “pre-releases”.
[src:containerd/releases] Major and minor releases of containerd will be made from main.
[src:containerd/releases] Releases of containerd will be marked with GPG signed tags and announced at https://github.com/containerd/containerd/releases .
[src:containerd/releases] The tag will be of the format `v<major>.<minor>.<patch>` and should be made with the command `git tag -s v<major>.<minor>.<patch>`.
[src:containerd/releases] After a minor release, a branch will be created, with the format `release/<major>.<minor>` from the minor tag.
[src:containerd/releases] All further patch releases will be done from that branch.
[src:containerd/releases] For example, once we release `v1.0.0`, a branch `release/1.0` will be created from that tag.
[src:containerd/releases] All future patch releases will be done against that branch.
[src:containerd/releases] Since containerd v2.3 in April 2026, minor releases are provided on a time basis with a cadence of 4 months.
[src:containerd/releases] New minor releases are scheduled for April, August, and December of each year.
[src:containerd/releases] This cadence is synchronized with the Kubernetes release schedule to ensure that new features in containerd can be smoothly adopted by new Kubernetes releases.
[src:containerd/releases] The maintainers will maintain a roadmap and milestones for each release, however, features may be pushed to accommodate the release timeline.
[src:containerd/releases] If your issue or feature is not present in the roadmap, please open a Github issue or leave a comment requesting it be added to a milestone.
[src:containerd/releases] As part of synchronizing with the Kubernetes release schedule, containerd will cut beta and release candidates that align with the Kubernetes release cycle.
[src:containerd/releases] This allows for end-to-end testing of new Kubernetes features with a compatible containerd version before the final release of either project.
[src:containerd/releases] Patch releases are made directly from release branches and will be done as needed by the release branch owners.
[src:containerd/releases] Pre-releases, such as alphas, betas and release candidates will be conducted from their source branch.
[src:containerd/releases] For major and minor releases, these releases will be done from main.
[src:containerd/releases] For patch releases, it is uncommon to have pre-releases but they may have an rc based on the discretion of the release branch owners.
[src:containerd/releases] Support horizons will be defined corresponding to a release branch, identified by `<major>.<minor>`.
[src:containerd/releases] Regular (non-LTS) releases will be supported for 8 months after a *minor* release.
[src:containerd/releases] This means that we will accept bug reports and backports to these release branches until the end of life date.
[src:containerd/releases] Additionally, releases may have an extended security support period after the end of the active period to accept security backports.
[src:containerd/releases] This timeframe will be decided by maintainers before the end of the active status.
[src:containerd/releases] One release per year will be designated a Long Term Stable (*LTS*) release.
[src:containerd/releases] LTS releases are supported for at least two years after their initial *minor* (x.y.0) release.
[src:containerd/releases] The maintainers of the *LTS* branch may commit to a longer period or extend the support period as needed.
[src:containerd/releases] These branches will accept bug reports and backports until the end of life date.
[src:containerd/releases] They may also accept a wider range of patches than non-*LTS* releases to support the longer term maintainability of the branch, including library dependency, toolchain (including Go) and other version updates which are needed to ensure each release is built with fully supported dependencies.
[src:containerd/releases] Feature backports are up to the discretion of the maintainers who own the branch but should be rejected by default.
[src:containerd/releases] This combination of regular and LTS releases allows users to choose between adopting new features more quickly or prioritizing stability and longer support lifecycles.
[src:containerd/releases] Every release shall be assigned owners when entering into the beta stage of the release.
[src:containerd/releases] The initial release owners will be responsible for creating the releases and ensuring the release is on time.
[src:containerd/releases] Once the release is in rc, the release owners should be part of any discussion around merging impactful or risky changes.
[src:containerd/releases] Every release should have at least two owners who are all active maintainers and one of which has been a release owner in at least two prior releases.
[src:containerd/releases] Once the final release is out and the release branch moves to active, ownership will be transferred back over to all committers.
[src:containerd/releases] Active releases are maintained by all committers until the release reaches end of life or the branch transitions to *LTS*.
[src:containerd/releases] Every *LTS* release requires at least two maintainers to volunteer as owners.
[src:containerd/releases] The owners of the *LTS* release may step down or be replaced by another maintainer at any time if they can no longer support the release.
[src:containerd/releases] If no maintainers volunteer to own the *LTS* release after maintainers step down, the branch will end of life after 6 months of extended support with ownership transferred back to all committers.
[src:containerd/releases] The Kubernetes version matrix represents the versions of containerd which are recommended for a Kubernetes release.
[src:containerd/releases] Any actively supported version of containerd may receive patches to fix bugs encountered in any version of Kubernetes, however, our recommendation is based on which versions have been the most thoroughly tested.
[src:containerd/releases] See the Kubernetes test grid for the list of actively tested versions.
[src:containerd/releases] Kubernetes only supports n-3 minor release versions and containerd will ensure there is always a supported version of containerd for every supported version of Kubernetes.
[src:containerd/releases] containerd runs on a range of operating systems and CPU architectures, but the level of support we can provide varies by platform.
[src:containerd/releases] Support is limited by what we are able to build, test, and maintain.
[src:containerd/releases] A platform that we can fully test in CI can be supported more strongly than one we can only compile.
[src:containerd/releases] To make these differences explicit, platforms are organized into tiers.
[src:containerd/releases] A tier describes what the project commits to for a platform.
[src:containerd/releases] Tiers are forward-looking and apply to in-development and future releases.
[src:containerd/releases] Platforms may be demoted or removed if the project is no longer able to commit to support at a given tier.
[src:containerd/releases] A platform is identified by its `GOOS/GOARCH` pair, optionally with a variant (for example `linux/amd64`, `windows/amd64`, or `linux/arm/v7`).
[src:containerd/releases] For operating systems like Linux, we do not designate specific distributions as supported, however automated testing primarily covers Ubuntu, Fedora, and AlmaLinux.
[src:containerd/releases] containerd’s build, testing, and release infrastructure is primarily defined in GitHub Actions .
[src:containerd/releases] Release artifacts and their platforms are defined in `release.yml`, nightly builds in `nightly.yml`, functional testing in `ci.yml`, and Tier 3 compile coverage in the `binaries` and `crossbuild` jobs of `ci.yml`.
[src:containerd/releases] This table should be updated if the workflows are changed.
[src:containerd/releases] New platforms enter at the lowest tier that the maintainers can sustainably commit to, and most begin at Tier 3.
[src:containerd/releases] To propose a new platform or a change in tier, open an issue describing the platform, its `GOOS/GOARCH`, the level of support being requested, and what you are able to contribute toward it.
[src:containerd/releases] Tiers reflect what the project can sustain, so a platform may move down as well as up.
[src:containerd/releases] When practical, the maintainers will give notice before lowering a platform’s tier or removing it, and will prefer to make such changes at a minor-release boundary.
[src:containerd/releases] Removing a platform does not retroactively affect artifacts already published for prior releases.
[src:containerd/releases] Backports in containerd are community driven.
[src:containerd/releases] As maintainers, we’ll try to ensure that sensible bugfixes make it into *active* release, but our main focus will be features for the next *minor* or *major* release.
[src:containerd/releases] For the most part, this process is straightforward, and we are here to help make it as smooth as possible.
[src:containerd/releases] An exception to the general policy of primarily backporting bugfixes is for new deprecation warnings.
[src:containerd/releases] To ensure users have adequate time to respond to upcoming breaking changes, new deprecation warnings may be backported to any supported release, including LTS releases.
[src:containerd/releases] Open a PR with cherry-picked change from main.
[src:containerd/releases] Remember that backported PRs must follow the versioning guidelines from this document.
[src:containerd/releases] Any release that is “active” can accept backports.
[src:containerd/releases] Opening a backport PR is fairly straightforward.
[src:containerd/releases] The steps differ depending on whether you are pulling a fix from main or need to draft a new commit specific to a particular branch.
[src:containerd/releases] Apply it to the release branch:`$ git cherry-pick -xsS <commit>`If all of the work from a particular PR/set of PRs is wanted, cherry-pick the individual commits instead of the merge commit.
[src:containerd/releases] Take #8624 for example, 82ec62b is favored over 9e834e7.(Optional) If other commits exist in the main branch which are related to the cherry-picked commit; eg: fixes to the main PR.
[src:containerd/releases] It is recommended to cherry-pick those commits also into this same `my-backport-branch`.
[src:containerd/releases] Push the branch and open up a PR against the *release branch*:Make sure to replace `stevvooe` with whatever fork you are using to open the PR.
[src:containerd/releases] When you open the PR, make sure to switch `main` with whatever release branch you are targeting with the fix.
[src:containerd/releases] If there is no existing fix in main, you should first fix the bug in main, or ask us a maintainer or contributor to do it via an issue.
[src:containerd/releases] Once that PR is completed, open a PR using the process above.
[src:containerd/releases] Only when the bug is not seen in main and must be made for the specific release branch should you open a PR with new code.
[src:containerd/releases] Upgrades are supported for sequential minor releases.
[src:containerd/releases] For example, an upgrade from 2.0 to 2.1 is supported, but an upgrade from 2.0 to 2.2 is not.
[src:containerd/releases] Patch releases are always backward compatible with their minor version.
[src:containerd/releases] In addition to sequential minor release upgrades, direct upgrades between sequential LTS (Long Term Stable) releases are also supported.
[src:containerd/releases] For example, a direct upgrade from 1.7 (LTS) to 2.3 (LTS) will be tested and supported, but 1.7 (LTS) to 2.6 (LTS, tentatively) will not.
[src:containerd/releases] This allows users who prefer to stay on LTS releases to have a clear and safe upgrade path.
[src:containerd/releases] There are no compatibility guarantees with upgrades to *major* versions.
[src:containerd/releases] For 2.0, migration was added to ensure upgrading from 1.6 or 1.7 to 2.0 is easy.
[src:containerd/releases] The latest releases of 1.6 and 1.7 provide deprecation warnings if any configuration is used which is incompatible with 2.0.
[src:containerd/releases] If deprecation warnings are showing up, the configuration can be safely migrated in 1.6 or 1.7 before upgrading to 2.0.
[src:containerd/releases] Once no deprecation warnings are showing up, the upgrade to 2.0 should be smooth.
[src:containerd/releases] Always check the release notes, breaking changes are listed there, and test your configuration before upgrading.
[src:containerd/releases] Features can only be removed in a release that immediately follows an LTS release.
[src:containerd/releases] Before upgrading, especially across multiple minor versions or to a new LTS release, users should ensure that they have addressed any deprecation warnings from their current version.
[src:containerd/releases] This practice ensures a smoother transition and avoids issues with removed features.
[src:containerd/releases] From the version stated in the above table, that component must adhere to the stability constraints expected in release versions.
[src:containerd/releases] Unless explicitly stated here, components that are called out as unstable or not covered may change in a future minor version.
[src:containerd/releases] Breaking changes to “unstable” components will be avoided in patch versions.
[src:containerd/releases] Go client API stability includes the `client`, `defaults` and `version` package as well as all packages under `pkg`, `core`, `api` and `protobuf`.
[src:containerd/releases] All packages under `cmd`, `contrib`, `integration`, and `internal` are not considered part of the stable client API.
[src:containerd/releases] The primary product of containerd is the GRPC API.
[src:containerd/releases] As of the 1.0.0 release, the GRPC API will not have any backwards incompatible changes without a *major* version jump.
[src:containerd/releases] To ensure compatibility, we have collected the entire GRPC API symbol set into a single file.
[src:containerd/releases] At each *minor* release of containerd, we will move the current `next.pb.txt` file to a file named for the minor version, such as `1.0.pb.txt`, enumerating the support services and messages.
[src:containerd/releases] Note that new services may be added in *minor* releases.
[src:containerd/releases] New service methods and new fields on messages may be added if they are optional.
[src:containerd/releases] `*.pb.txt` files are generated at each API release.
[src:containerd/releases] They prevent unintentional changes to the API by having a diff that the CI can run.
[src:containerd/releases] These files are not intended to be consumed or used by clients.
[src:containerd/releases] As of containerd 2.0, the API version diverges from the main containerd version.
[src:containerd/releases] While containerd 2.0 is a *major* version jump for containerd, the API will remain on 1.x to remain backwards compatible with prior releases and existing clients.
[src:containerd/releases] The 2.0 release adds the API to a separate Go module which can remain as the `github.com/containerd/containerd/api` Go package and imported separately from the rest of containerd.
[src:containerd/releases] The API minor version will continue to be incremented for each major and minor version release of containerd.
[src:containerd/releases] However, the API is tagged directly out of the main branch with the minor version incrementing earlier in the next release cycle rather than at the end.
[src:containerd/releases] This means that after the containerd 2.0 release, the next API change is tagged as `api/v1.9.0` prior to any containerd 2.1 release.
[src:containerd/releases] The latest API version should be backported to all supported versions and patch releases for prior API versions should be avoided if possible.
[src:containerd/releases] The metrics API that outputs prometheus style metrics will be versioned independently, prefixed with the API version. i.e.
[src:containerd/releases] The metrics API version will be incremented when breaking changes are made to the prometheus output.
[src:containerd/releases] New metrics can be added to the output in a backwards compatible manner without bumping the API version.
[src:containerd/releases] containerd is based on a modular design where plugins are implemented to provide the core functionality.
[src:containerd/releases] Plugins implemented in tree are supported by the containerd community unless explicitly specified as non-stable.
[src:containerd/releases] Out of tree plugins are not supported by the containerd maintainers.
[src:containerd/releases] Currently, the Windows runtime and snapshot plugins are not stable and not supported.
[src:containerd/releases] Please refer to the GitHub milestones for Windows support in a future release.
[src:containerd/releases] Error codes will not change in a patch release, unless a missing error code causes a blocking bug.
[src:containerd/releases] Error codes of type “unknown” may change to more specific types in the future.
[src:containerd/releases] Any error code that is not “unknown” that is currently returned by a service will not change without a *major* release or a new version of the service.
[src:containerd/releases] If you find that an error code that is required by your application is not well-documented in the protobuf service description or tested explicitly, please file an issue and we will clarify.
[src:containerd/releases] Unless explicitly stated, the formats of certain fields may not be covered by this guarantee and should be treated opaquely.
[src:containerd/releases] For example, don’t rely on the format details of a URL field unless we explicitly say that the field will follow that format.
[src:containerd/releases] As of containerd 2.0, the Go client API documented in godoc is stable.
[src:containerd/releases] Note that because the Go client interfaces with the GRPC API, clients building on top of the Go client should remain compatible with future server releases implementing the same major GRPC API series.
[src:containerd/releases] For backwards compatability and as a general rule of thumb, it is the client’s responsibility to handle not implemented errors returned by the containerd daemon.
[src:containerd/releases] Any changes to the Go client API should be detectable at compile time, so upgrading will be a matter of fixing compilation errors and moving from there.
[src:containerd/releases] The CRI (Container Runtime Interface) GRPC API is used by a Kubernetes kubelet to communicate with a container runtime.
[src:containerd/releases] This interface is used to manage container lifecycles and container images.
[src:containerd/releases] Currently, this API is under development and unstable across Kubernetes releases.
[src:containerd/releases] Each Kubernetes release only supports a single version of CRI and the CRI plugin only implements a single version of CRI.
[src:containerd/releases] Each *minor* release will support one version of CRI and at least one version of Kubernetes.
[src:containerd/releases] Once this API is stable, a *minor* will be compatible with any version of Kubernetes which supports that version of CRI.
[src:containerd/releases] The `ctr` tool provides the ability to introspect and understand the containerd API.
[src:containerd/releases] It is not considered a primary offering of the project and is unsupported in that sense.
[src:containerd/releases] While we understand its value as a debug tool, it may be completely refactored or have breaking changes in *minor* releases.
[src:containerd/releases] Targeting `ctr` for feature additions reflects a misunderstanding of the containerd architecture.
[src:containerd/releases] Feature addition should focus on the client Go API and additions to `ctr` may or may not be accepted at the discretion of the maintainers.
[src:containerd/releases] We will do our best to not break compatibility in the tool in *patch* releases.
[src:containerd/releases] The daemon’s configuration file, commonly located in `/etc/containerd/config.toml` is versioned and backwards compatible.
[src:containerd/releases] The `version` field in the config file specifies the config’s version.
[src:containerd/releases] If no version number is specified inside the config file then it is assumed to be a version `1` config and parsed as such.
[src:containerd/releases] The configuration is automatically migrated to the latest version on each startup, leaving the configuration file unchanged.
[src:containerd/releases] To avoid the migration and optimize the daemon startup time, use `containerd config migrate` to output the configuration as the latest version.
[src:containerd/releases] All prior versions are supported by migration.
[src:containerd/releases] Migrating a configuration to the latest version will limit the prior versions of containerd in which the configuration can be used.
[src:containerd/releases] It is suggested not to migrate your configuration file until you are confident you do not need to quickly rollback your containerd version.
[src:containerd/releases] Use the table of configuration versions to containerd releases to know the minimum version of containerd for each configuration version.
[src:containerd/releases] As a general rule, anything not mentioned in this document is not covered by the stability guidelines and may change in any release.
[src:containerd/releases] Between upgrades of subsequent, *minor* versions, we may migrate these formats.
[src:containerd/releases] Any outside processes relying on details of these file system layouts may break in that process.
[src:containerd/releases] Container root file systems will be maintained on upgrade.
[src:containerd/releases] We may make exceptions in the interest of **security patches**.
[src:containerd/releases] If a break is required, it will be communicated clearly and the solution will be considered against total impact.
[src:containerd/releases] Experimental features are new features added to containerd which do not have the same stability guarantees as the rest of containerd.
[src:containerd/releases] An effort is made to avoid breaking interfaces between versions, but changes to experimental features before being fully supported is possible.
[src:containerd/releases] Users can still expect experimental features to be high quality and are encouraged to use new features to help them stabilize more quickly.
[src:containerd/scope] Having a clearly defined scope of a project is important for ensuring consistency and focus.
[src:containerd/scope] These following criteria will be used when reviewing pull requests, features, and changes for the project before being accepted.
[src:containerd/scope] Components should not have tight dependencies on each other so that they are able to be used independently.
[src:containerd/scope] The APIs for images and containers should be designed in a way that when used together the components have a natural flow but still be useful independently.
[src:containerd/scope] An example for this design can be seen with the overlay filesystems and the container execution layer.
[src:containerd/scope] The execution layer and overlay filesystems can be used independently but if you were to use both, they share a common `Mount` struct that the filesystems produce and the execution layer consumes.
[src:containerd/scope] containerd should expose primitives to solve problems instead of building high level abstractions in the API.
[src:containerd/scope] A common example of this is how build would be implemented.
[src:containerd/scope] Instead of having a build API in containerd we should expose the lower level primitives that allow things required in build to work.
[src:containerd/scope] Breaking up the filesystem APIs to allow snapshots, copy functionality, and mounts allow people implementing build at the higher levels with more flexibility.
[src:containerd/scope] For the various components in containerd there should be defined extension points where implementations can be swapped for alternatives.
[src:containerd/scope] The best example of this is that containerd will use `runc` from OCI as the default runtime in the execution layer but other runtimes conforming to the OCI Runtime specification can be easily added to containerd.
[src:containerd/scope] containerd will come with a default implementation for the various components.
[src:containerd/scope] These defaults will be chosen by the maintainers of the project and should not change unless better tech for that component comes out.
[src:containerd/scope] Additional implementations will not be accepted into the core repository and should be developed in a separate repository not maintained by the containerd maintainers.
[src:containerd/scope] The following table specifies the various components of containerd and general features of container runtimes.
[src:containerd/scope] The table specifies whether or not the feature/component is in or out of scope.
[src:containerd/scope] containerd is scoped to a single host and makes assumptions based on that fact.
[src:containerd/scope] It can be used to build things like a node agent that launches containers but does not have any concepts of a distributed system.
[src:containerd/scope] containerd is designed to be embedded into a larger system, hence it only includes a barebone CLI (`ctr`) specifically for development and debugging purpose, with no mandate to be human-friendly, and no guarantee of interface stability over time.
[src:containerd/scope] The scope of this project is a whitelist.
[src:containerd/scope] If it’s not mentioned as being in scope, it is out of scope.
[src:containerd/scope] For the scope of this project to change it requires a 100% vote from all maintainers of the project.
